<p>Britpop legends Oasis took the UK by storm in August when they announced they were reuniting, 15 years after their storied breakup. Brothers Liam and Noel Gallagher, who had spent the last decade and a half in a deep feud, put their differences aside to announce a 15-date stadium tour across the UK next summer, with US dates also released.</p>
<p>Live music tours have had a major economic impact on local economies in recent years, turning into cultural events in their own right, as seen with Beyoncé's Renaissance Tour and Taylor Swift's Eras Tour. Oasis sold out their 15 UK dates as quickly as ticketing platforms would allow, with unprecedented demand from fans to see the Gallaghers on stage together again. The host cities, London, Manchester, Cardiff, and Dublin, stand to see a substantial economic boost to hospitality, retail, and transport businesses as a result.</p>
<p>In the 30 years since Oasis released their debut album, Definitely Maybe, a lot has changed in consumer relationships within fashion and retail. Even so, cultural events and nostalgia remain effective tools for brands looking to capitalize on the current Oasis fever.</p>

<h2>Live forever</h2>
<p>The Oasis reunion is a reminder that some bands, and some brands, never lose their place in the public's affection. The 90s bridged music, fashion, and lifestyle to create some of the most iconic trends in fashion history, and Oasis were central to the Britpop movement that shaped the era's aesthetic: parka coats, bucket hats, Fred Perry polos, and Adidas trainers. The reunion gives brands an opening to tap into that resurgence, launching retro-inspired collections or limited-edition items that capture Britpop style while appealing to today's audience.</p>

<h2>The masterplan</h2>
<p>There's still a year to go before the Oasis concerts take place, and a number of brands are already moving to capitalize on the nostalgia. Manchester City Football Club, long associated with Noel Gallagher, launched a kit celebrating the Definitely Maybe album, named "Definitely City," timed just after the reunion announcement. Around the same time, Liam Gallagher was announced as the new face of Stone Island, fronting the brand's autumn and winter campaign in a parka that has become synonymous with his name.</p>
<p>Adidas is another brand to watch. For over 30 years, the Gallagher brothers have been closely associated with the Superstar, Gazelle, and Samba sneakers, which became part of the Oasis image well beyond footwear. Adidas's roots in working-class Manchester and football terrace culture align closely with the band's ethos, and the brand was already producing Oasis-inspired footwear before the reunion was announced. Streaming platforms including Apple TV, Amazon Prime, and Netflix are reportedly competing to film the reunion tour, and more fashion retailers are likely to follow with their own tie-ins.</p>

<h2>Don't look back in anger</h2>
<p>Oasis's 2025 reunion is more than a concert tour. It's a cultural moment set to influence fashion, marketing, and live music, reviving 90s staples like bucket hats, baggy jeans, and oversized parkas for a new generation of fans. The resurgence of 90s nostalgia is already fueling fashion and pop culture trends that retailers can build campaigns around, giving brands a real opportunity to create experiences that resonate with fans old and new.</p>
